ful men. In pursuing their desires, the putains challenge contemporary notions of womanhood and expose the injustices of ancien-régime France. Until the French Revolution spelled the end of the genre, these novels proposed not only an appealing libertine utopia in which libertine women enjoy the same benefits as their male counterparts but also entirely new ways of looking at systems of power, gender, and sexuality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAutobiographical fiction, FrenchxHistory and criticism. 0aFrench fictiony18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLibertines in literature. 0aProstitutes in literature. 0aWomen in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aLa Belle Allemande, Margot la ravaudeuse, La Cauchoise, Histoire de Juliette, Juliette, Sade, gender studies, women's studies, eighteenth-century studies, eighteenth-century France, French studies, French history, literary studies, pre-revolutionary France, ancien-régime France, French literature, libertine literature, memoir novel, sexuality, sex work, eighteenth-century prostitute, female libertines, putain, putains, female friendship, feminine networks.40uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978164453326040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781644533260423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781644533260/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles